[[ch06-overview-low-confidence-science]]
== Overview: Low Confidence Science

Imagine for a second a blank sheet of paper. Further imagine a solid black line in the middle of the page. On the left of the line is the word "History". On the right of the line is "Social Engineering".

We like to pretend that those who forget the past are doomed to repeat it. If that were the case then we could use history as technical models to provide social engineering, the right side of our imaginary page. But it doesn't work. History cannot come close to science in providing models that can be used to control future outcomes.

Now, let's take our imaginary page and replace "History" with "Philosophy". In some sense philosophy is a distillation of history to create models to predict human behavior. Here's the thing. Philosophy has no more success than just using history. History and philosophy both rely on something we call hindsight. Hindsight fits the facts to the model and ignores everything that would invalidate the hindsight "prediction".

The failure of history and philosophy to provide any social engineering models of even slight success is why engineers such as myself "poo poo" history and philosophy as just ego trips.

Social engineering is built on science. Not history. Not philosophy. Social engineering uses the same methodologies for social engineering as any other other field of science.

Social science is a long established field. We have over a century of research.

So where are we at? Well, sadly, not far along. Social science is limited in scope, meaning it's local to a small amount of time and number of people. Arguably social science is not much more capable than history or philosophy.

Take for example violence. Studies have been conducted on whether video games cause violence or reduce violence. There have been studies on pornography where prisoners were allowed access to pornography one year before release and then their crime rate compared to normal prisoners released at the same time. Have these studies born much fruit? Not much. The studies being inconclusive are valuable in debunking unfounded claims that video games cause violence or that pornography causes violence. The truth is that we still don't know.

So what's going on here?

Let's set our eyes on what is arguably one of the most reliable pieces of social science to date: violence caused by poverty.

My very first investigation into social science was when I was in high school. I wanted to know if capital punishment reduced crime. Back in the 1970s there was a very public movement to ban capital punishment as inhumane. The advocates for capital punishment claimed without proof that capital punishment reduces crime.

Back in the 1970s Time magazine regularly included scientific reporting. Just using years of Time magazine articles in our city library I was able to piece together reports that all the studies linking capital punishment to crime reduction were inconclusive. There were too many variables to take into consideration. However, one variable that has on outsized influence on human behavior is poverty. Studies have repeatedly shown that high rates of poverty correlate to increased levels of violence such that poverty could be safely called a cause for violence and not just a correlation.

As far as I know this violence science still holds true today.

My second investigation into social science happened in college. I was interested in whether gun ownership reduced home invasion deaths. Gun advocates claim without evidence that guns reduce homeowner deaths. I wanted to see what science showed. The best study I could find was one conducted by the New York Police department. That study showed that in fact guns in the home increased the rate of homeowner death during a home invasion. There were two primary factors listed. First, the best strategy to survive a home invasion is to run. Always have exit paths mapped out. Homeowners with guns choose to stay and fight. The second primary factor is that homeowners are generally not prepared to kill someone. This was juxtaposed to the criminal. The criminal is amped up on adrenaline whereas perhaps the home owner is woken from their sleep. The criminal has mentally prepared to shoot before entering the house. This preparation increased the accuracy of the criminals in a shootout. The criminal was mentally prepared to shoot and mentally prepared to shoot to kill. The NYC police study showed home owners were more likely to die in a home invasion if they owned a gun because a.) they didn't run, and b.) they weren't prepared to shoot and shoot to kill. Further, homeowners are not trained for situational awareness. This lead homeowners to shoot through walls and kill other household members.

However, this NYC Police study was only one study so I wouldn't base nation-wide policy on it.

I've read many more social science reports and studies. The conclusion I have today is that at best social science has low confidence on a large scale. Social science improves accuracy when variables or conditions are constrained to local time and space.

At this point one may be wondering then why rely on social science at all if it is barely more effective than history or philosophy in predicting human behavior?

Well, there are two reasons. Low confidence is not no confidence. Second, future studies can continue to improve on low-confidence effectiveness.

Okay, but how does one conduct low-confidence science? The answer is trial-and-error experiments based on existing low confidence science.

Therefore Irreni Society is an experimental society. Every project conducted by MGOs is considered an experiment. Every single one. MGOs only coordinate with projects, projects that are always experiments. 

All project contracts being experiments means hypotheses are made. Expected outcomes are given. Measurements are made. Results are reported. The thesis here is that we can improve on social science efficacy by running millions upon millions of experiments where today we only have a few thousand.

Everyone will be aware of the improvement in social engineering as well as all the failures.

Another feature of experimental social science society is that all projects as experiments must be proven at a small scale before being implemented at a larger scale. Today, projects that roll out at a large scale initially are not experiments, they are ideological projects. Take, for example, the American Care Act, ACA. The ACA was initially rolled out at a national level that included all Americans. At a minimum it should have been rolled out for a single State to start. Successes and failures could have been analyzed and then another round conducted with two States. Then maybe ten States. But no, the ACA was rolled out to all fifty States in the first go. The fact that the ACA was rolled out to all fifty States in its first round means that it can't be an experiment. There are no States without ACA influence to compare too.


We are starting to build a picture here of how to conduct low-confidence science. First, every social project is an experiment. Second, every experiment must start small and succeed before being tried at larger scales. But this is still not the best we can do.

Another improvement to our low-confidence science is simulation. The best example today of simulation is environment impact studies. These studies simulate what will happen to the environment when a project is implemented.

Irreni Society conducts simulation using an Earth AI. This Earth AI is used to simulate projects before implementation. These simulations have multiple benefits:
1. Approvals based upon simulation outcomes.
2. Simultaneous simulation of new and current projects. Project simulation is not performed in isolation. Instead project simulation is run side-by-side with other new projects proposed as well as current projects running.
3. Experiment result validation. The initial project outcomes will be suggested without simulation. Their initial approval will then be simulated and new outcomes will be created while being balanced against other projects running. Finally the end results will be recorded and compared to the Earth AI experimental outcomes predicted.

So we have three steps for conducting low-confidence science:

1. Every project is considered an experiment and written as such.
2. Every experiment must be proven to work at smaller scales before trying larger scales.
3. Earth AI simulation is used to analyze new experiments being conducted alongside other new and current experiments.

This is a huge undertaking but one that must be done in order to be able implement social projects that actually work as opposed to just ideological projects of no proven efficacy.

In the previous chapter the weird aspect of always viewing every social effort as an experiment was left out. However, this experimental society is weird relative to today's societies where laws are made based on ideology alone without any regard as to any confidence they will succeed.

Irreni Society is an experimental society. It is not an ideological society. The distinction allows Irreni Society to effectively dissolve existing ideological governments by proving social projects work at a small scale before committing larger resources.
